To rus Enrnnon Tanain

lr is enacted, Sir, by the provincial code which Pompey drew up for Bithynas that no person shall exercise any magistracy, or be admitted into the senate, under the age of thirty. By the same law it is provided, that those who have held a magistracy shall be senators of course. Subsequently, however, an edict of the Emperor Augustus permitted minor offices to be held at the age of twenty-two. The question therefore is, whether those who 'have held office before the age of thirty, may be legally admitted into the senate by the Consors, and if so, whether by the same kind of construction they may be admitted senators, at the age when they are allowed to be magistrates, though they llave not actually borne any office. A custom‚ it seems, which has hitherto been observed, and is said to be necessary, as it is a good deal better that persons of noble birth should be admitted into the senate, than those of plebeian rank.
